=========
EvilCandy
=========

---------------------------------------------
A Script Interpreter and Programming Language
---------------------------------------------

:Author: Paul Bailey <roscidcup@falstaffandme.com>
:Date: April 2025

About
=====

**EvilCandy** is a(nother) object-oriented interpreted programming
language and interpreter.  The language itself is nothing original;
I cherry-picked some of my favorite syntactic features of Python
and JavaScript, and put them together in the same language.  That
may sound strange, like some Frankenstein's monster of a language,
but I took pains to adapt features that work naturally together.
I'd say that EvilCandy is JavaScript-like in its syntax and overall
appearance, as well as its slightly lambda-ish nature, but it is
Python-like in many of its basic data types, built-in functions, and
underlying machinery.  The real purpose of the project is in the
challenge of writing an interpreter and virtual machine, not
inventing a paradigm-changing language.

But despite being influenced by those languages, it is not either of
them, nor is it an off-brand version of them, like Octave to MATLAB,
or a lightweight 'embedded' version, like Cash to jQuery.  EvilCandy
immitates JavaScript and Python only as a starting point, but its
continuing development makes no effort to conform to them in any way.
In many ways, it diverges greatly.

Status
======

**UNSTABLE!!**  See disclaimer in COPYING.  The language and its
implementation are under rapid development.  The version in this branch
is currently prealpha.x.

As of April 2026, the following can (roughly) be said about EvilCandy:

* It "works," but it still has elementary bugs that I keep finding and
  tracking down.  (See "issues" tab on GitHub.)

* It parses an input, compiles it into binary code, then executes it
  in a virtual stack machine.  When debug hooks are turned off (which
  in truth it's not ready for), its speed for basic execution is
  comparable to Python, at least on my computer; string and list handling
  is probably much slower, but I haven't rigorously tested that stuff
  yet.

* It can run in interactive mode, although it's a bit quirky; I haven't
  figured out a good solution to statements where the parser needs to
  "peek" at the next token, so if you type an "if" statement and do not
  intend to add and "else" statement, you need to type a superfluous
  semicolon to let the parser know to execute it...that kind of quirky.
  (See issue #48.)

* It can run in disassembly mode, where instead of executing code,
  it will disassemble its compiled input and print it.  Probably not
  useful to anybody but me, as a debugging tool.

* It can load and execute scripts, and have those scripts load and
  execute scripts.

* I have not yet added in any code for cyclic GC, so there's a hazard
  of accidentally immortalizing data with cyclic references, for example
  when inserting a dictionary into itself.

* It has the skeleton of a math, IO, and socket library, but these are
  mainly as they were when I threw them together just to see if
  something works.

* Generators are supported, but comprehension expressions are not.

* It is single-threaded.

* It does not support externally-linkable C modules.  Currently all the
  C code has to be compiled into a single binary.

* I have thus far only run this on Darwin and Ubuntu, and compiled it
  with clang and gcc.

* I have not finished making all my final decisions about syntax.  I am
  considering adding static typing, which will gut out a lot of the
  language's existing syntax.  That is a very post-alpha issue to resolve.

* For now, the cleanest way to inherit a base class is to actually
  inherit it.  But EvilCandy also has features to make Composition Over
  Inheritance more pleasant, using a "by" keyword in a class declaration.

* It has all the characteristics of a source tree that has been maintained
  by just one person without someone else stress-testing it.  It is loaded
  with thrown-together code that needs refactoring and make-professional-ing.
  There is not a lot of portability checking.  Currently the test code
  consists of a couple scripts in tests/, some unit tests in
  programs/unit_tests.c and a fuzzer test in programs/fuzzer.c.

So no, EvilCandy is not a ship-able release candidate.

Some FAQ
========

Why Is It Called EvilCandy?
---------------------------

I wanted to call it CandyScript, but I found out that "Candy Script" was
already the name of a popular typeface—if "popular typeface" is a thing
that can exist.  So I settled for EvilCandy.

How Is It Different From JavaScript?
------------------------------------

In a nutshell, the resemblance between EvilCandy and JavaScript is mostly
cosmetic.  The biggest similarities are (1) statements are delimited by
braces and semicolons (and more strictly so than in JavaScript), instead
of line endings; and (2) function definitions are treated as literal
expressions, so they may be stated just about anywhere, even as arguments
to other functions.

Here are some major differences...

* There is no ``var`` keyword.  There are only ``let`` and ``global``.

* The ``for`` loop resembles Python's for loop rather than JavaScript's
  C-like for loop.  This also means that where speed is a concern, you
  can avoid the frame-swapping overhead that comes with an array's or
  dictionary's ``.foreach`` built-in method.

* EvilCandy has a ``range`` data-type like Python, to facilitate using
  the Python-like for-loop for general-purpose do-this-a-million-times
  iterating.

* EvilCandy is very dynamically typed.  However, a recent nighttime visit
  by three ghosts showed me the true spirit of safe programming, so a
  distant-future version will be more hybrid in this respect.

* Most of EvilCandy's built-in methods were modeled after Python rather
  than JavaScript.  While writing this interpreter I was thinking about
  JavaScript while keeping an eye on some Python pocketbooks.  For
  example, ``join`` is a string method, not a list method.

* When I get to work on the module library (see Status_) I have no
  intention of trying to continue making it resemble JavaScript.

* I really like the ``else`` clause to Python's ``for`` loop, so I
  implemented a ``for`` loop that has an optional ``nobreak`` statement.
  I chose ``nobreak`` instead of ``else`` in EvilCandy's case, as a guard
  against the hazard that comes with not using braces around a ``for``
  statement which contains an ``if`` statement.

* EvilCandy has nothing to do with the Document Object Model.

* EvilCandy is more bare-bones with its native types.  There is a
  ``class`` syntax, but no ``this.Prototype.Init`` or whatnot.

* EvilCandy's classes inherit base classes and build up a MRO array
  rather than use a JavaScript-like ``Prototype`` chain.  It also
  permits a single delegate object per class instance, for programmers
  who prefer the Composition Over Inheritance approach.  For extending
  built-in classes, this is necessary, because inheritance is only
  permitted for user-defined classes.

* Associative arrays are not class instantiations; they are just pure
  dictionaries.  As with JavaScript, you could combine closures and
  dictionaries in a way that forgoes ``class`` syntax altogether, but
  you have to be more particular about it, because EvilCandy has no
  ``this`` keyword.

How Fast Is EvilCandy?
----------------------

As of 2026 the only benchmarking I've done on EvilCandy is the hillbilly
kind: I run a brute-force square root algorithm that iterates over input
values from one to a million, and time it.  An equivalent algorithm in
Python takes about 4-5s to complete on my computer.  Ever since I got
the VM (src/vm.c) working, my own interpreter is roughly the same, 4-5s.

But one, that only speed-tests basic execution of assembled instructions.
It doesn't stress test any worst-case scenarios, like abusively long
lists or strings, large quantities of small variables, things like that.

Two, the Python-like speed is mostly an illusion. I could only get it
to run that fast when compiling ``-O3 -DNDEBUG``, which the program is
not ready for.  With all the debug hooks and bug traps left in, it's
about a third as fast.

And three, EvilCandy is very lightweight.  Things may change when I
start adding in more features.

Still, this is not embarrassing, and I'm quite proud of how fast it runs.

How Do I Compile?
-----------------

To compile the source tree as checked out of version control, you
need to reconfigure with

.. code::

        autoreconf -i
        ./configure

Then you type ``make`` in the command line.

Be aware that I have only ever compiled this on Darwin and occasionally
on Ubuntu.  I have tried to avoid system-specific functionality, and I
occasionally compile with ``-std=c17 -pedantic-errors``.  I'm trying
where possible to avoid gcc-specific extensions, but since clang seems to
call itself gcc, it's hard to tell if I'm succeeding.  Computers built in
Obscuresylvania or the 1970s (or worse, computers running Windows 😊)
probably will not execute this program correctly.  It's hard to not
accidentally make assumptions about a system when you're the only developer
on a project.  So I make no promise that it will compile on your system,
especially if it is a Windows system.

The Language
============

If you have Sphinx, go to Documentation and run ``make html``.
If you do not, the restructuredText files in Documentation/tutorial
should be human-readable enough.  But disregard the Documentation/langref/
and Documentation/libref/.  These are wildly out of date.

